{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c3b68382-1ac5-44e4-b059-3ce9af744563","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT since it's a CoreCLR tool), you can use the **OS-native crash reporting**:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** via the shell before running your app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **If `/cores` is missing or SIP blocks it**, create and permission it:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./YourApp\n   ```\n\n5. For richer .NET diagnostics, you can also use **`dotnet-dump analyze`** on the core file (if the SDK is installed), though support for NativeAOT dumps is limited compared to CoreCLR.\n\n**Key takeaway:** Since NativeAOT produces a fully native binary, you rely on OS-level crash infrastructure (`/cores`, DiagnosticReports) rather than the managed `createdump` tool.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8fa69138-053c-4e74-b438-b3e3de54dad9","outputTokens":350,"requestId":"640E:3ED481:150726D:1888E79:69EC1A13"},"id":"d4b50e06-7d2d-4747-a020-d8f9555d361f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:34:28.325Z","parentId":"19feb32c-c4eb-4a83-b611-d5c491d273f4"}
